  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency drought response to emergency health needs in Baghis; in complement to CHF 2018 2nd allocation</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Through the implementing partner, National NGO AYSO in Badghis, ACF will implement integrated emergency healthcare through mobile health teams (MHTs) including mobile psychosocial support. To broaden the scope of reach, avoid duplication and capitalize on ACF&#x2019;s current learning on both application to and implementation of CHF, (now AHF),  MHTs in Badghis will be implemented by current partner AYSO (already working in Badghis) and will (in addition to doctor, screener, midwife and PSS officer already covered under CHF 2nd allocation), include 1 Nurse per to deliver IMNCI, and 1 vaccinator to support vaccination. It is necessary to integrate the IMNCI for prevention of recurring pathologies in Nutrition (triggering or complicating cases of malnutrition) response, however, as health response it is also a clear health activity to respond to the diarrhea and respiratory infections that have increased. ACF&#x2019;s holistic integrated MHT model, now well established with a strong evidence base, shows the integration of IMNCI, ANC, PNC, PSS and vaccination supports the best response for the individual early development needs in the most vulnerable and hard to reach areas. This model reduces burden on the beneficiary by delivering in real time a comprehensive package of support, mitigating any delays, which can rapidly take childhood illnesses such as pneumonia and diarrhea. By identifying specific vulnerabilities and providing physical rehabilitation and psychological support services to these vulnerable groups the action will reduce their vulnerability and will mitigate the impact of the drought by facilitating access to lifesaving services, improving functional capacities and independence, strengthening positive coping mechanisms, promoting wellbeing, and reducing the chances of psychological distress. 
Overall, this project is in strong compliment to the recent CHF funded drought response allocation to ACF for Nutrition and Protection (start date September 2018), for the overall reduction of rates of mortality and morbidity in most vulnerable populations as a result of the drought in priority districts. ACF will implement comprehensive partnerships and security access plans (see sections below), in coordination with a surveillance plan on nutritional, health and psychosocial needs to circulate findings to all Health stakeholders.</narrative>
  </description>
